node.text: @unoriginal.catholic yes I’ve seen that study as well. Again, that doesn’t list the people that don’t identify with anything - which is important to take into consideration. I do see that Gallup’s study has tried to replicate this study now.  This issue absolutely needs to be considered as a global issue and not limited to a single country - especially when considering how many individuals move country in order to access services not available where they were born. Our stats of pro-choice v anti-abortion belief here in Australia, for instance, stands in start contrast to those of America - with 85-90% saying they are pro-choice and only 4% saying that abortion is never right in any circumstance. I would have to say our greatly lower rates of religious identification will have something to do about that. As well as looking into the options of developed countries, I strongly encourage you to look at statistics across the globe. We really can’t form an opinion of right and wrong by remaining isolated in our understanding. It may also help you understand how access to abortion has been linked with class issues - in developing countries in particular - and see the class and racial implications of this debate. I’ve gone into some of them lower in this thread if you’re interested.
@esme.louisee I will try to look into the abortion statistics from other countries to widen my view, thanks for the advice
